,Not Recommended,248390,31027356,Posted: 8 April,all,Ole Greg,"Craft the World: 6-7/10.-4 World types to build the ultimate dwarf fortress.-Each world has it's own unique dangers and environmental challenges.-Each time you get a certain amount of experience points, you get 1 more dwarf (up to 13 I believe) and unlock new things to craft.Con: A very poor crafting system. Each recipes has to be hand placed the first time, before you're allowed to mass produce an item. When you have dozen upon dozens of crafting recipes these can be very irriating. Plus the craft tree made you have to craft every recipe to get to the higher ones, with the game progression this often meant having useless gear that just needed to be crafted to get to the next tier of crafting. Mindless grind.Con: Complete lack of a storyline, even though story like elements appear in the game.Con: Each dwarf has three skills that can be leveled up. Although those skills don't seem to actually benefit the dwarf in any noticeable way. Nor are the dwaves drawn to their choosen profession. Just because a dwarf is a logger, doesn't mean they'll be the ones cutting the trees down (and again the skills don't actually add anything).Con: And this is huge. While the game doesn't take up much space, every time they come out with a new DLC, it automatically downloads into your game and needs to be unlocked (purchased) to be used.  And what's more the DLC's all seem to be a feature that should have been part of the initial game. For instances one DLC allows for faster dwarves that look vaguely female. Another allows for multiplayer. If you're going to download it onto my computer, and then require me to buy a feature that should have come out with the normal game, it's going to♥♥♥♥♥♥some people off. Honestly while I'm normally against pirating games these DLC's make me want to break those personal rules.Conclusion: I know I've listed mostly con's, and if you can pickup this game at a large discount I'd recommend buying it to try if you like sandbox games. But overall it's a very shallow game. It has a tablet game type feel that tried to be a real PC game and failed horribly.Overall with the fact it automatically downloads the DLC without purchasing the game and then requires you to unlock it, when the DLC should have been a normal feature of the game instead of a ""we want more money"" DLC; has me thinking I'm going to avoid games coming from this company in the future.A side note to the Dekovir Entertainment. Here's a suggestions for a future game DLC. Call it the ""Options"" DLC. For just 10 bucks you get the ability to adjust sound settings, maybe change screen resolutions."
,Recommended,248390,18538501,"Posted: 17 October, 2015",all,Aurumlamina,"Though not a Game of the Year by any means, Craft the World is a fun game that will keep you entertained in short bursts.  It can be best described as Terraria if it were an RTS where you were in charge of a tribe of dwarves instead of just your hero and, of course, there was significantly less content to discover.Your tasks in the game include gathering resources, feeding and caring for your dwarves, researching technologies, building defensive structures, and digging deeper and deeper.  Each and every dwarf is an individual with skills that can be learned and improved and equipment that can be upgraded as you develop the technology and acquire the neccessary resources t ocraft it.  Though it was exciting to acquire new technology, it was often tedious working through the previous tech to fill your research bar as you are required to craft the same three or four items many, many times.Though it is enjoyable and I believe that it is worth it at a sale price under $10, the game does grow old rather quickly and, if you're anything like me, you'll find yourself burning out toward the end of the first of five worlds.  I recommend this for fans of resource gathering and building games (Terraria/Minecraft), though, as stated earlier, it is more of an RTS as you are in charge of several dwarves at a time."
