76561198056914826,Recommended,248390,13435816,"Posted: 18 December, 2014",all,smg_bear,"I find it very fun, but I don't like that I cannot start on a world that I have already unlocked.  It is either start from world 1 or play some random world.  The little guys are funny when they start attacking."
,Recommended,248390,13558651,"Posted: 23 December, 2014",all,K!netic,"tl;dr Buy it, you'll have fun. But don't expect to love it forever.Let's cut to it - it's not as interactive as it looks. You set commands (""cut down that tree"", ""mine that shaft"", ""place that item"", ""gather water"", ""plant wheat here"", etc) on blocks. The dwarves then decide which tasks they want to do, and when. Each dwarf can only do one task at a time, and you don't get to control the priority of tasks (though combat orders always seem to be the most important). This means that if you wind up setting up orders for a new tunnel, a logging operation, planting a new crop, and building the house, the dwarves will do it in whatever order they want. You can't decide the order. One of your dozen dwarves (it's hard to get more than 12 dwarves) will get around to it eventually.And for much of the game, that's fine, and you won't complain. But as others have noted, endgame it becomes a chore. Dwarves need to input/output items into the central (immovable) stockpile for practically every task, and they wind up traversing huge distances to do so. This becomes a huge bottleneck, and wastes obscene amounts of time. You'd think that one dwarf could cut a tunnel while others removed the stone behind him; but nope. One dwarf cuts as much stone as he can hold, then makes a full trip back to home to drop it off, then comes back. If you order a dwarf to patch a hole in the wall with dirt, dwarves that are currently HOLDING DIRT will just pass right by the wall, and one specific dwarf will grab dirt from the stockpile, then patch the wall with it.This is especially stupid because you can't move stockpiles, nor can you create stockpiles for a *very long time*. If you're playing tech tree mode, it's literally the second-to-last thing you unlock (~12ish hours of gameplay). If you're playing sandbox, it's all luck which things you unlock, but you still won't have the ability to build a stockpile for many hours - if you get it at all.There's the option to use railroads, but they're expensive (they take a lot of iron to traverse a Large map), and like stockpiles, aren't unlocked until late in the game.The fix for this is to use portals. You drop a portal from your stockpile to wherever you want your dwarves to work, it drastically shortens the trip time, and they prefer tasks near the portal. But that's a terrible solution, in my mind. It shortcuts the whole idea of ""building"" and having good task scheduling, and instead makes it so that you micromanage portals instead of dwarves.Ultimately, it's fun for a good amount of hours. But it doesn't increase in depth or complexity, and becomes a grind to unlock things that you don't even want by the time you get them."
,Recommended,248390,13269236,"Posted: 7 December, 2014",all,TheSilverHammer,"This is an OK game. It is not great, but it might amuse you for a little while.  Its probabbly best bought on sale.The Good:It is a crafting / exploration game.  There are far to few of these.  It has a wide tech-tree with lots of objects and stuff to build.  The world generation is decent too although there isn't enough coal in the small worlds.  I had to buy a lot from a vendor.  If you are really into making an asthetically nice dwarf city, you might get more milage out of the decoration options.The bad:The UI can use some work and it is a little annoying.  You can't see recipies in creative mode.  It would be nice to have this option.  Once you complete a world there isn't much point in doing another one.  You will face the exact same challenges all over again.  There is no real difference in gameplay.  This game could certainly use a lot of mods to make it far more interesting.Mana:  You mana refiels 1 point every 3 minutes or fully when you levelup. This is a terrible design.  The most useful spell, one you start with, opens a portal between your stockpile and some other point.  You can easily drain your mana with this and as you get higher level, it takes much longer to levelup and refil the mana.  There are these large invasions that happen every 45 minutes. I think your mana should refil after these instead of the 1 point per 3 minutes.  There are mana potions, but they take a lot of resources to make and give very little mana.The Ugly:The tech tree is horribly laid out.  It forces you to crank out a bunch of useless stuff in order to progress  and there isn't a logical connection between most items.  For example: You need to learn advanced decorating before you can learn advanced armors.  The tree is full of stuff like this.  Just re-arranging the tech tree could go a long way to improving this game.  You know: If it went with Basic wood working -> Adanced Wood working -> Expert wood working, etc... it would make much more sense.Then there are the skills your dwarves can use.  Some skills go up like crazy, such as cooking.  Others, such as magery, I think I gained 3 points in one dwarf the entire game.  Then some things that do not seem to have skills, like alchemy.  Making potions is slow, and a dwarf after making like 80 of them didn't gain any kind of skills and was just as slow as before.Finally, there isn't much of a challenge in this game.  You just fight the occasionaly wave of undead which ceases to be a problem once you get decent armor and weapons.  It seems that spike barraceds are the best answer for defense.  The towers in the game, arrow and tesla, seem very weak.  Twoard the end, it was a dull experience."
