76561197978782798,Not Recommended,248390,18153497,"Posted: 22 September, 2015",all,Corvus Dove,"Have you ever wanted to be suckered into buying a mobile device game on your PC?  Are you tired of the subtle humor and gameplay for all ages in things like Terraria and looking for something that will give you tedium and a complete lack of control?  Craft The World is the game for you!Gone are the days where you have to do all that pesky mining yourself in a matter of seconds!  Gone are the days where your construction is in an open world and the universe is your oyster!  Imagine, for a moment, some of the greatest games in strategy platformer gaming history.  The Lemmings. The Humans.  Now imagine all of the aspects of those games that made you want to pull your hair out, and here we are!I picked this up because Steam recommended it because Terraria.   This has paid off before..Starbound, Edge of Space, etc.  This game plays nothing like those.  Instead, you have command of a dwarf or two and give them commands to build stuff and harvest resources.  What shows that this was originally a mobile game?  You wait.  And wait.  Then there's more waiting.   In 10 minutes I had done 5 things.  3 of those were in another window.  I'm not sure why this was so highly recommended, as my opinion of this game is that it is microtransaction tripe ported to PC with all of the appeal of recycled laxatives."
76561198098450112,Recommended,248390,14275975,"Posted: 1 February, 2015",all,Dark Divinity,"SEX!Huzah!  Now I have your attention.As far as God-simulators go, this game is pretty awesome.  The game has a surprising amount of depth and a creative sandbox mode once you complete the 3 level campaign which adds to the fun.  The campaign consists of 3 levels: first is a small forest setting, the second is a medium sized snow setting, and the last is a large desert, each getting more difficult to pass.  Don't be fooled by the few levels though, each one has taken me upwards of 10 hours each to finish.Over the course of a game, you have to start with nothing much like other creation games such as Minecraft, and build your way up from nothing by gathering everything from dirty to iron, gold, and eventually Mithril.  Using these gathered resources, you traverse a large tech tree, each category allowing you to build more items ranging from decoration for your home to weapons and armor.The game will pique your interest quick and hold your attention for a long time.  With that said, once you beat the campaign and do a sandbox mode or two, you start to notice and exploit things like how to efficiently mine, find gold or skill books, and how to cheese the invading zombies (I will not reveal that here.)  Once this happens, you (or at least I did) will get bored quickly.  The novelty for me wore off literally halfway through a game one day, and I just quit.The Good:1-Great crafting system2-Challenging combat (not at first, but the longer you stay in game, the more enemies come out to ransack you)3-very fun spellunking system4-hours upon hours of fun per level5-quests give you both direction and rewardThe Bad:1-Once you've discovered combat and mining exploits, the game loses most of its fun and challenge2-Even the largest maps are pretty small, taking maybe only 25% more time to finish than the smallest3-Enemy waves happen only once every 50 minutes (25 minutes if you have the game speed set to 2x)4-weapon and armor improvements are WAY down the tech tree, so you have inferior gear against large waves if you dont move fastAll in all, the game is a great way to burn a lot of hours, especially for how cheap it is.  being under $20 means that as long as you enjoy it for at least 10 hours, it was well worth it, and I promise you will get a lot more than that out of it."
