,Recommended,248390,8268909,"Posted: 24 December, 2013",all,Darkrite,"While there remains a few pathing bugs, small features that lack intuitive design--such as a larger warning for design flaws with the dwarven abode and where to fix those flaws--I still find this one enjoyable. The battle features are lacking, with the advancing waves leaving much to be desired. If only there was a premise or reason for the waves constantly attacking and a gradual increase in difficulty that were visually represented, this would complete the experience for me. With that being said however, this is a gamer's vacation away from other games, without waxing enthusiastic on the crafting genre. There have been a few games that cut into this genre that do a very poor job with design, yet this is not one of them. The technical advancement tree is well thought out and makes sense in terms of rhythmic play. The way lighting and terrain plays into the game leaves you patching up every possible angle of defense and lighting every corridor possible to stave off the encroaching threat. I believe this will do well if the developers improve the AI of the dwarves (and enemies) to include line of sight issues with ranged weapons and add diversity to the threats themselves."
